metadata.name: The Hum of Cyber Forest #201
metadata.description:
The forest exists as a noise, a hum of ever-changing states. 
The forest is chaos. 
The forest is technological, as it is filled with an uninterrupted seething of information, the exchange of pollen dust.

The rhythmic song of a cyborg shaman mingling with this noise evokes disintegrating, pixelated visions.

Rhythms of tree trunks are made with a help of DALL·E mini neural network and were inspired by surrealistic painters.
Thanks Yulikolay for helping. The dithering code was inspired by a number of examples, links to which are indicated in the work’s code.

metadata.name: Ries #494
metadata.description:
Ries is 500 sheets of paper. 
Ries is an cut-up text-artwork.
Ries is artwork generated by an algorithm based on seeded random numbers.
Ries is a digital artwork installed in 5 forms in exhibitions setting.
Ries is an NFT artwork. 

Ries is an artwork where I try bring together my experience of doing gallery exhibitions, my love for generative and copy machine art, DIY-punk aesthetics, NFT’s and chaos. 

The edition of Ries will be installed in different forms and collages in a gallery exhibition in Walden Kunstaustellungen in Berlin in July of 2022. Opening is at 8.7. 19.00, welcome if you are in Berlin.
/www.galerie-walden.de/

The seed idea for the project was the method of cut-up where a text (or something else) is cut into pieces and then rearranged to form something new. A modified Markov’s Chain algorithm makes a small text or a group of words from a pool of texts that include Art texts about cut up technique and generative art talk from tweets. These words form a visual bottom layer and then another layer of words samples the first, cutting it up and thus following the theme of the artwork.

Since the single iterations of the project are designed to be used in a collage, they come in various tone, density, detail and scale. One can test from the variations button and get a sense of what the generator produces. 

Controls in live view:
-Pressing  j exports the current image as jpeg
-Pressing  p  exports the current image as png

To change the detail level one can access the pixel density of render by adding ?pixDens=4 to the end of the URL in live view. You can of course you any number other than 4 also. I it renders just a black image, you have to lower the number, since it is then too large for WEBGL to render.

Designed to be best rendered on desktop Chrome.

Pricing info
22 tez - Includes a gallery shown, signed print sent to minter by mail or by telefax(!)
11 tez - A fair price for an artwork, also the minter can personally pick up a signed gallery shown print from the gallery, after the exhibition.
5 tez - 1/2 fair price
2 tez - bottom dollar

If you minted on lower tiers and would want a print, please contact the artist per twitter dm to “upgrade”. If you bought secondary, and would want a print, please contact the artist per twitter dm.

Features exist mostly to help with artwork pairing for the collectors.


Markov’s chain code core is based on Markov Me! By https://codepen.io/alexkramerbanjo , MIT License

Displacement shader based on the wonderful shader examples by Adam Ferris


The artist holds the right to use the whole edition of Ries for display purposes for future exhibitions without asking permission or notifying the owners of the NFT’s.

1.7.2022 in Berlin
Antti Pussinen

www.anttipussinen.net
www.twitter.com/antti_pussinen
www.instagram.com/anttipussinen

metadata.name: Mini Dahlias #249
metadata.description:
Welcome to the enchanting world of "Mini Dahlias" - a mesmerizing generative art project that will spark joy in your heart! Unleashing the magic of algorithms, each miniature masterpiece blooms with vibrant colors and whimsical patterns, transporting you to a dreamy realm of creativity.

But wait, there's more to this fantastical journey! Nestled within each digital artwork lies a hidden treasure - an embedded blueprint that holds the secret to crafting a tangible, real-life edition. Picture it: delicate petals brought to life in the physical realm, ready to be gifted or cherished!

Twenty exquisite physical editions of “mini Dahlias,” crafted with love are destined to be gifted by a friend of mine to random strangers at Burning Man, where creativity knows no bounds!

Inspired by spreading joy and creativity, "Mini Dahlias" is available on fxhash, ensuring that this delightful experience can be enjoyed by art enthusiasts worldwide. Embrace the charm, share the magic, and let the artistry of algorithms paint smiles across the universe. Happy creating and sharing the wonder! 🎨✨

metadata.name: Lookouts #79
metadata.description:
Lookouts is a generative illustration done 100% in code using p5js. Inspired by my love for travel and minimalist design, this collection is built based on custom shapes filled with solid colors & limited texture.

The accompanying fxtext article (in ‘Mentions’ below) shares more details about the inspiration and development process of this project.

Lookouts renders as a fixed resolution output (2000 x 1666px). Controls (in live view): 
Press [4] to render at 4000 x 3333px
Press [8] to render at 8000 x 6666px
Press [s] to save the current view (default or higher resolution image)

metadata.name: Fractal Painting #194
metadata.description:
This is composition art based on mathematics fractal.

Color Pallet has 10 variations.
Frame Line has 2 variations.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [f] to switch full screen on and off
- Press [s] to download a PNG file with windowsize
- Press [l] to download a PNG file with large size 4800 pixel (wait a minutes)

Create with p5.js
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Moonlit Sea #12
metadata.description:
A few years ago, my son and I went on a long-term trip to Taitung, Taiwan. One night on the roof of the B&B, we saw the moonlight falling on the pacific ocean. It was very beautiful and peaceful. We will never forget this scene.

Made with memory and p5js.

Variables:
- 24 palettes + random colors
- 5 moon shapes
- 2 island patterns
- 5 wave strength

Control(in live view):
- Press [s] to save a high-res png image

metadata.name: the Glory of Colours #131
metadata.description:
According to Kandinsky, painting “can create the same energies in the observer that music can make in the listener. The abstract painter is an echo seeker: just like the relationship between music and the listener, shapes and colors must penetrate the observer's soul. They vibrate the threads of his existence and resonate in the depths of his mind, you can still find references to people, buildings, mountains, etc., but these are more signs than manifestations. They do not evoke objects but abstractly reveal them, like the simplified image we have seen before of objects and elements in nature.
Classical philosophy reinforces the belief that existing, tangible reality is a mask for a deeper reality that can only be reached through imagination. I have tried to combine this with the art of coding and creating canvases of millions of characters and numbers.
Made in p5js
Created July 2022
Artist: @ChistaAi
